{"title_page": "Waqar Zaka", "text_new": "{{short description|Pakistani television host, editor, actor, VJ, concept writer, director, producer}}\n{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Waqar Zaka\n| nationality   = Pakistani\n| alma_mater    =\n| birth_place   = [[Sargodha]], [[Pakistan]]\n| occupation    = [[Television host]]\n| years_active  = 2005\u2013present\n| known_for     = [[Living on the Edge (Sabse Himmat Wala Kon?)|Living on the Edge]]<br>[[Champions Hosted By Waqar Zaka|Champions]]\n|website = http://waqarzaka.net\n}}\n\n'''Waqar Zaka''' is a Pakistani [[Radio personality|radio jockey]]-turned-television host.<ref name=\"tribune/14feb2013\">{{cite news|title=I am giving Pakistanis a platform to vent their frustrations: Waqar Zaka - The Express Tribune|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/507331/i-am-giving-pakistanis-a-platform-to-vent-their-frustrations-waqar-zaka/|accessdate=1 July 2017|work=The Express Tribune|date=14 February 2013}}</ref> \n\n==Early life==\nZaka claims to have done engineering from [[NED University of Engineering & Technology]].\n\nWaqar began his career during his school life by releasing the student song ''Nahi Parha Meine Poora Saal'' and then became [[Radio personality|radio jockey (RJ)]]. After earning fame as RJ, he started hosting a TV [[reality show]] [[Living on the Edge: Sabse Himmat Wala Kon?|Living on the Edge]].<ref name=\"dawnnews/28may2019\">{{cite news |last1=\u0688\u06cc\u0633\u06a9 |first1=\u0627\u0646\u0679\u0631\u0679\u06cc\u0646\u0645\u0646\u0679 |title=\u0648\u0642\u0627\u0631 \u0630\u06a9\u0627 \u0646\u0648\u062c\u0648\u0627\u0646\u0648\u06ba \u06a9\u0648 \u0628\u06be\u0679\u06a9\u0627\u0646\u06d2 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0627 \u0645\u0648\u0627\u062f \u062a\u06cc\u0627\u0631 \u06a9\u0631\u0646\u06d2 \u067e\u0631 \u0634\u0631\u0645\u0646\u062f\u06c1 |url=https://www.dawnnews.tv/news/1104219 |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Dawn News Television |date=28 May 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"dawn/7march2009\">{{cite news|title=Chit chat Meet Waqar Zaka|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/448557/chit-chat-meet-waqar-zaka|accessdate=1 July 2017|work=DAWN.COM|date=7 March 2009|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"tribune/14feb2013\" /> Waqar then created and hosted [[reality shows]] ''XPOSED'',<ref name=\"dawn/7march2009\" /> ''King of Street Magic'',<ref name=\"dawn/7march2009\" /> ''Desi Kudiyan'' and ''The Cricket Challenge'' aired on [[ARY Musik]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/879155/i-am-the-reason-why-some-people-now-rule-the-entertainment-industry-waqar-zaka/|title=I am the reason why some people now rule the entertainment industry: Waqar Zaka|work=The Express Tribune|first=Sameen|last=Hassan|accessdate=22 June 2015|date=4 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2013 Pakistani general election]], Zaka ran for the seat of the [[National Assembly of Pakistan]] from [[Constituency NA-253|Karachi NA-253]] constituency,<ref>{{cite news|title=Waqar Zaka says 'Line Pe Ajao' - The Express Tribune|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/837229/waqar-zaka-says-line-pe-ajao/|accessdate=1 July 2017|work=The Express Tribune|date=12 February 2015}}</ref> but was unsuccessful<ref name=\"dawnnews/28may2019\" /> and secured only 31 votes out of the 211,768 total votes cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ecp.gov.pk/Documents/Downloads/General%20Election%202013/Detailed%20Gazzette/Notification%20-%20National%20Assembly.pdf|title=Election Commission of Pakistan Notification|work=Election Commission of Pakistan|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> Zaka claims he ran to demonstrate how to run for election for his show ''Main Banoonga Minister''; he stated that this was \"the only entertaining way of telling our youth how to be a part of the system\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mahmood |first1=Rafay |title=I am giving Pakistanis a platform to vent their frustrations: Waqar Zaka |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/507331/i-am-giving-pakistanis-a-platform-to-vent-their-frustrations-waqar-zaka/ |accessdate=22 August 2019 |work=The Express Tribune |date=14 February 2013 |language=en}}</ref> He ran on a platform of prioritizing and improving access to entertainment and the internet.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/529514/waqar-zaka-hopes-to-go-from-cobra-to-constituency/|title=Waqar Zaka hopes to go from cobra to constituency - The Express Tribune|date=1 April 2013|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=1 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aaj.tv/2013/04/main-banoonga-minister-waqar-zaka-strives-to-contest-elections/|title=Main Banoonga Minister: Waqar Zaka strives to contest elections|last=Ishtiaque|first=Aqsa|work=Aaj News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128123043/https://www.aaj.tv/2013/04/main-banoonga-minister-waqar-zaka-strives-to-contest-elections/|access-date=5 June 2018|archive-date=28 November 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, he announced a political movement in Pakistan called Tehreek-e-Tech.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.samaa.tv/lifeandstyle/2019/04/we-may-never-see-waqar-zaka-on-tv-again/ | title=We may never see Waqar Zaka on TV again | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419213558/https://www.samaa.tv/lifeandstyle/2019/04/we-may-never-see-waqar-zaka-on-tv-again/ | accessdate=19 April 2019| archive-date=19 April 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"dailytimes1\">{{cite web | url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/375662/waqar-zaka-to-launch-cryptocurrency-to-help-pakistan-pay-off-its-debts/ | title=Attention seeking Waqar Zaka claims he wants to launch cyrptocurrency to help Pakistan pay off its debts | date=11 April 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412131604/https://dailytimes.com.pk/375662/waqar-zaka-to-launch-cryptocurrency-to-help-pakistan-pay-off-its-debts/ | accessdate=19 April 2019| archive-date=12 April 2019 }}</ref> In May 2019, he apologized to the people for destroying the young minds during his TV reality show ''Living on the Edge''.<ref name=\"dawnnews/28may2019\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Waqar Zaka seeks apology from nation for destroying young minds |url=http://dunyanews.tv/en/Entertainment/493945-Waqar-Zaka-seeks-apology-nation-destroying-young-minds/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Dunya News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190530064649/http://dunyanews.tv/en/Entertainment/493945-Waqar-Zaka-seeks-apology-nation-destroying-young-minds/ |archive-date=30 May 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Champions With Waqar Zaka==\nIn November 2019, Zaka began hosting a TV reality show ''[[Champions (Pakistani TV series)|Champions With Waqar Zaka]]'' on [[BOL Network]].<ref name=\"pakistantoday/10april2020\" /> In January 2020, the TV show ''Champions With Waqar Zaka'' was banned by [[Pakistan Electronic Media Regulatory Authority]] (PEMRA)<ref name=\"pakistantoday/10april2020\">{{cite news |title=Waqar Zaka's show 'Champions' to remain suspended, IHC rules - Pakistan Today |url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/04/10/waqar-zakas-show-champions-remain-suspended-ihc-rules/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=www.pakistantoday.com.pk |date=10 April 2020}}</ref> for being \"offensive towards social, religious and cultural values of this country\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Waqar Zaka's Show Champions Gets Banned By PEMRA |url=https://propakistani.pk/lens/waqar-zakas-show-champions-gets-banned-by-pemra/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Lens |date=10 April 2020}}</ref> In April 2020, the [[Islamabad High Court]] upheld the decision of PEMRA to ban ''Champions With Waqar Zaka''. <ref>{{cite news |last1=\u0688\u06cc\u0633\u06a9 |first1=\u0648\u06cc\u0628 |title=\u0642\u0627\u0628\u0644 \u0627\u0639\u062a\u0631\u0627\u0636 \u0645\u0648\u0627\u062f \u0646\u0634\u0631 \u06a9\u0631\u0646\u06d2 \u067e\u0631 \u0628\u0648\u0644 \u0679\u06cc \u0648\u06cc \u06a9\u06d2 \u067e\u0631\u0648\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645 \u0686\u06cc\u0645\u067e\u06cc\u0626\u0646\u0632 \u067e\u0631 \u067e\u0627\u0628\u0646\u062f\u06cc \u0628\u0631\u0642\u0631\u0627\u0631 |url=https://www.dawnnews.tv/news/1125800 |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Dawn News Television |date=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the suspension of his TV reality show ''[[Champions (Pakistani TV series)|Champions With Waqar Zaka]]'', he began hosting a late night show on YouTube called ''Headphone Show''. The show was  criticised for \"constant swearing\" and \"inappropriate conversations\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Lewd headphone show designed to help audience, insists Waqar Zaka {{!}} SAMAA |url=https://www.samaa.tv/entertainment/2020/04/lewd-headphone-show-designed-to-help-audience-insists-waqar-zaka/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Samaa TV|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413074930/https://www.samaa.tv/entertainment/2020/04/lewd-headphone-show-designed-to-help-audience-insists-waqar-zaka/ |archive-date=13 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 2017, he received an award from [[Abdul Qadeer Khan]] for his social and humanitarian work in the war-torn areas of Syria and Myanmar.<ref>{{cite news|title=Waqar Zaka receives award from Dr Abdul Qadeer Khan|url=http://nation.com.pk/snippets/31-Mar-2017/waqar-zaka-receives-award-for-his-humanitarian-services|accessdate=8 July 2017|work=The Nation}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|6680650}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zaka, Waqar}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:VJs (media personalities)]]\n[[Category:Pakistani television hosts]]\n[[Category:People from Karachi]]\n[[Category:Pakistani stunt performers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People from Sargodha]]\n[[Category:NED University of Engineering and Technology alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Pakistani television host, editor, actor, VJ, concept writer, director, producer}}\n{{pp-semi-indef}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Waqar Zaka\n| nationality   = Pakistani\n| alma_mater    =\n| birth_place   = [[Sargodha]], [[Pakistan]]\n| occupation    = [[Television host]]\n| years_active  = 2005\u2013present\n| known_for     = [[Living on the Edge (Sabse Himmat Wala Kon?)|Living on the Edge]]<br>[[Champions Hosted By Waqar Zaka|Champions]]\n|website = http://waqarzaka.net\n}}\n\n'''Waqar Zaka''' is a Pakistani [[Radio personality|radio jockey]]-turned-television host.<ref name=\"tribune/14feb2013\">{{cite news|title=I am giving Pakistanis a platform to vent their frustrations: Waqar Zaka - The Express Tribune|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/507331/i-am-giving-pakistanis-a-platform-to-vent-their-frustrations-waqar-zaka/|accessdate=1 July 2017|work=The Express Tribune|date=14 February 2013}}</ref> \n\n==Early life==\nZaka claims to have done engineering from [[NED University of Engineering & Technology]].<ref name=\"dailytimes1\" />\n\nWaqar began his career during his school life by releasing the student song ''Nahi Parha Meine Poora Saal'' and then became [[Radio personality|radio jockey (RJ)]]. After earning fame as RJ, he started hosting a TV [[reality show]] [[Living on the Edge: Sabse Himmat Wala Kon?|Living on the Edge]].<ref name=\"dawnnews/28may2019\">{{cite news |last1=\u0688\u06cc\u0633\u06a9 |first1=\u0627\u0646\u0679\u0631\u0679\u06cc\u0646\u0645\u0646\u0679 |title=\u0648\u0642\u0627\u0631 \u0630\u06a9\u0627 \u0646\u0648\u062c\u0648\u0627\u0646\u0648\u06ba \u06a9\u0648 \u0628\u06be\u0679\u06a9\u0627\u0646\u06d2 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0627 \u0645\u0648\u0627\u062f \u062a\u06cc\u0627\u0631 \u06a9\u0631\u0646\u06d2 \u067e\u0631 \u0634\u0631\u0645\u0646\u062f\u06c1 |url=https://www.dawnnews.tv/news/1104219 |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Dawn News Television |date=28 May 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"dawn/7march2009\">{{cite news|title=Chit chat Meet Waqar Zaka|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/448557/chit-chat-meet-waqar-zaka|accessdate=1 July 2017|work=DAWN.COM|date=7 March 2009|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"tribune/14feb2013\" /> Waqar then created and hosted [[reality shows]] ''XPOSED'',<ref name=\"dawn/7march2009\" /> ''King of Street Magic'',<ref name=\"dawn/7march2009\" /> ''Desi Kudiyan'' and ''The Cricket Challenge'' aired on [[ARY Musik]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/879155/i-am-the-reason-why-some-people-now-rule-the-entertainment-industry-waqar-zaka/|title=I am the reason why some people now rule the entertainment industry: Waqar Zaka|work=The Express Tribune|first=Sameen|last=Hassan|accessdate=22 June 2015|date=4 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2013 Pakistani general election]], Zaka ran for the seat of the [[National Assembly of Pakistan]] from [[Constituency NA-253|Karachi NA-253]] constituency,<ref>{{cite news|title=Waqar Zaka says 'Line Pe Ajao' - The Express Tribune|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/837229/waqar-zaka-says-line-pe-ajao/|accessdate=1 July 2017|work=The Express Tribune|date=12 February 2015}}</ref> but was unsuccessful<ref name=\"dawnnews/28may2019\" /> and secured only 31 votes out of the 211,768 total votes cast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ecp.gov.pk/Documents/Downloads/General%20Election%202013/Detailed%20Gazzette/Notification%20-%20National%20Assembly.pdf|title=Election Commission of Pakistan Notification|work=Election Commission of Pakistan|accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref> Zaka claims he ran to demonstrate how to run for election for his show ''Main Banoonga Minister''; he stated that this was \"the only entertaining way of telling our youth how to be a part of the system\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mahmood |first1=Rafay |title=I am giving Pakistanis a platform to vent their frustrations: Waqar Zaka |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/507331/i-am-giving-pakistanis-a-platform-to-vent-their-frustrations-waqar-zaka/ |accessdate=22 August 2019 |work=The Express Tribune |date=14 February 2013 |language=en}}</ref> He ran on a platform of prioritizing and improving access to entertainment and the internet.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/529514/waqar-zaka-hopes-to-go-from-cobra-to-constituency/|title=Waqar Zaka hopes to go from cobra to constituency - The Express Tribune|date=1 April 2013|work=The Express Tribune|accessdate=1 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.aaj.tv/2013/04/main-banoonga-minister-waqar-zaka-strives-to-contest-elections/|title=Main Banoonga Minister: Waqar Zaka strives to contest elections|last=Ishtiaque|first=Aqsa|work=Aaj News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181128123043/https://www.aaj.tv/2013/04/main-banoonga-minister-waqar-zaka-strives-to-contest-elections/|access-date=5 June 2018|archive-date=28 November 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2019, he announced a political movement in Pakistan called Tehreek-e-Tech.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.samaa.tv/lifeandstyle/2019/04/we-may-never-see-waqar-zaka-on-tv-again/ | title=We may never see Waqar Zaka on TV again | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190419213558/https://www.samaa.tv/lifeandstyle/2019/04/we-may-never-see-waqar-zaka-on-tv-again/ | accessdate=19 April 2019| archive-date=19 April 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"dailytimes1\">{{cite web | url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/375662/waqar-zaka-to-launch-cryptocurrency-to-help-pakistan-pay-off-its-debts/ | title=Attention seeking Waqar Zaka claims he wants to launch cyrptocurrency to help Pakistan pay off its debts | date=11 April 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412131604/https://dailytimes.com.pk/375662/waqar-zaka-to-launch-cryptocurrency-to-help-pakistan-pay-off-its-debts/ | accessdate=19 April 2019| archive-date=12 April 2019 }}</ref> In May 2019, he apologized to the people for destroying the young minds during his TV reality show ''Living on the Edge''.<ref name=\"dawnnews/28may2019\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Waqar Zaka seeks apology from nation for destroying young minds |url=http://dunyanews.tv/en/Entertainment/493945-Waqar-Zaka-seeks-apology-nation-destroying-young-minds/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Dunya News|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190530064649/http://dunyanews.tv/en/Entertainment/493945-Waqar-Zaka-seeks-apology-nation-destroying-young-minds/ |archive-date=30 May 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Champions With Waqar Zaka==\nIn November 2019, Zaka began hosting a TV reality show ''[[Champions (Pakistani TV series)|Champions With Waqar Zaka]]'' on [[BOL Network]].<ref name=\"pakistantoday/10april2020\" /> In January 2020, the TV show ''Champions With Waqar Zaka'' was banned by [[Pakistan Electronic Media Regulatory Authority]] (PEMRA)<ref name=\"pakistantoday/10april2020\">{{cite news |title=Waqar Zaka's show 'Champions' to remain suspended, IHC rules - Pakistan Today |url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2020/04/10/waqar-zakas-show-champions-remain-suspended-ihc-rules/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=www.pakistantoday.com.pk |date=10 April 2020}}</ref> for being \"offensive towards social, religious and cultural values of this country\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Waqar Zaka's Show Champions Gets Banned By PEMRA |url=https://propakistani.pk/lens/waqar-zakas-show-champions-gets-banned-by-pemra/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Lens |date=10 April 2020}}</ref> In April 2020, the [[Islamabad High Court]] upheld the decision of PEMRA to ban ''Champions With Waqar Zaka''. <ref>{{cite news |last1=\u0688\u06cc\u0633\u06a9 |first1=\u0648\u06cc\u0628 |title=\u0642\u0627\u0628\u0644 \u0627\u0639\u062a\u0631\u0627\u0636 \u0645\u0648\u0627\u062f \u0646\u0634\u0631 \u06a9\u0631\u0646\u06d2 \u067e\u0631 \u0628\u0648\u0644 \u0679\u06cc \u0648\u06cc \u06a9\u06d2 \u067e\u0631\u0648\u06af\u0631\u0627\u0645 \u0686\u06cc\u0645\u067e\u06cc\u0626\u0646\u0632 \u067e\u0631 \u067e\u0627\u0628\u0646\u062f\u06cc \u0628\u0631\u0642\u0631\u0627\u0631 |url=https://www.dawnnews.tv/news/1125800 |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Dawn News Television |date=9 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the suspension of his TV reality show ''[[Champions (Pakistani TV series)|Champions With Waqar Zaka]]'', he began hosting a late night show on YouTube called ''Headphone Show''. The show was  criticised for \"constant swearing\" and \"inappropriate conversations\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Lewd headphone show designed to help audience, insists Waqar Zaka {{!}} SAMAA |url=https://www.samaa.tv/entertainment/2020/04/lewd-headphone-show-designed-to-help-audience-insists-waqar-zaka/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Samaa TV|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200413074930/https://www.samaa.tv/entertainment/2020/04/lewd-headphone-show-designed-to-help-audience-insists-waqar-zaka/ |archive-date=13 April 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 2017, he received an award from [[Abdul Qadeer Khan]] for his social and humanitarian work in the war-torn areas of Syria and Myanmar.<ref>{{cite news|title=Waqar Zaka receives award from Dr Abdul Qadeer Khan|url=http://nation.com.pk/snippets/31-Mar-2017/waqar-zaka-receives-award-for-his-humanitarian-services|accessdate=8 July 2017|work=The Nation}}</ref>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn January 2017, a video went viral on social media websites where Zaka was severely assaulted by a group of people in Karachi. Zaka was injured in the attack,<ref>{{cite news |title=TV anchor Waqar Zaka thrashed by unidentified man in Karachi - Entertainment - Dunya News |url=https://dunyanews.tv/en/Entertainment/372645-TV-anchor-Waqar-Zaka-thrashed-by-unidentified-man- |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=dunyanews.tv}}</ref> leaving his hand fractured.<ref>{{cite news |title=TV host Waqar Zaka assaulted {{!}} SAMAA |url=https://www.samaa.tv/news/2017/01/tv-host-waqar-zaka-assaulted/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Samaa TV}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=TV host Waqar Zaka assaulted in Karachi - Pakistan Today |url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2017/01/28/tv-host-waqar-zaka-assaulted-in-karachi/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=www.pakistantoday.com.pk}}</ref> Zaka later reconciled with his attacker.<ref>{{cite news |title=Drop scene: Waqar Zaka comes to terms with attacker {{!}} SAMAA |url=https://www.samaa.tv/culture/2017/02/drop-scene-waqar-zaka-comes-to-terms-with-attacker/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Samaa TV}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Waqar Zaka takes a \u0091U-turn\u0092 |url=https://dailytimes.com.pk/30562/waqar-zaka-takes-a-u-turn/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=Daily Times |date=6 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, media reported that Zaka was arrested by police in Karachi for possessing alcohol,<ref>{{cite news |title=Arrested for possession of sheesha not alcohol, Waqar Zaka clarifies |url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/396309-arrese |accessdate=28 January 2019 |work=www.thenews.com.pk |language=en}}</ref> however Zaka clarified that he was charged with possession of [[Hookah|sheesha]] instead of alcohol.<ref>{{cite news |title=Waqar Zaka arrested, denies possessing alcohol |url=https://tribune.com.pk/story/1850448/4-waqar-zaka-arrested-denies-possessing-alcohol/ |accessdate=28 January 2019 |work=The Express Tribune |date=19 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Waqar Zaka lashes out at media for reporting he was arrested for alcohol possession - Pakistan Today |url=https://www.pakistantoday.com.pk/2018/11/19/waqar-zaka-lashes-out-at-media-for-reporting-he-was-arrested-for-alcohol-possession/ |accessdate=15 April 2020 |work=www.pakistantoday.com.pk}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|6680650}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zaka, Waqar}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:VJs (media personalities)]]\n[[Category:Pakistani television hosts]]\n[[Category:People from Karachi]]\n[[Category:Pakistani stunt performers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:People from Sargodha]]\n[[Category:NED University of Engineering and Technology alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Madmax124", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fake news)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Waqar_Zaka"}
{"title_page": "Battle of Mu'tah", "text_new": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict          = Battle of Mu'tah<br>{{lang|ar|\u063a\u064e\u0632\u0652\u0648\u064e\u0629 \u0645\u064f\u0624\u0652\u062a\u064e\u0629}}<br>{{lang|ar|\u0645\u064e\u0639\u0652\u0631\u064e\u0643\u064e\u0629 \u0645\u064f\u0624\u0652\u062a\u064e\u0629}}\n| partof            = the [[Arab\u2013Byzantine wars]]\n| image             = Mausoleum ,Jafer-ut-Tayyar,Jordan.JPG\n| caption           = The tomb of Muslim commanders [[Zayd ibn Harithah]], [[Ja'far ibn Abi Talib]], and [[Abd Allah ibn Rawahah]] in Al-Mazar near [[Mu'tah]], [[Jordan]]\n| next_battle       = [[Battle of Yarmouk]]\n| date              = September 629{{sfn|Kaegi|1992|p=72}}\n| place             = [[Mu'tah]], [[Karak Governorate]], [[Jordan]], [[Syria (region)|Sham]]\n| result            = Byzantine political victory as it looked like a complete defeat but the Arabs had a strategic retreat engaging in small scale skirmishes, achieving a mild strategic victory{{sfn|Kaegi|1992|p=67}}{{sfn|Tucker|2010|p=200}}\n| combatant1        = [[Muslim conquests|Muslim Arabs]]\n| combatant2        = [[File:Simple_Labarum2.svg|15px]] [[Byzantine Empire]]<br>[[Ghassanids]]\n| commander1        = [[Zayd ibn Harithah]]{{KIA}}<br>[[Ja'far ibn Abi Talib]]{{KIA}}<br>[[Abd Allah ibn Rawahah]]{{KIA}}<br><ref name=zayd /> [[Khalid ibn Al-Walid]]\n| commander2        = [[Theodore (brother of Heraclius)|Theodore]]<br>[[Heraclius]]<br>[[Shurahbil ibn Amr]]\n| strength1         = 3,000{{sfn|Powers|2009|p=86}}\n| strength2         = 100,000 ([[Al-Waqidi]])<ref name=waqidi>{{Cite book| publisher = Cambridge University Press| isbn = 978-0-521-59984-9| last = Gil| first = Moshe| title = A History of Palestine, 634-1099| date = 1997-02-27|page=23}}</ref><br>200,000 ([[Ibn Ishaq]])<ref name=ishaq>{{Cite book| publisher = Oxford University Press, USA| isbn = 0-19-636033-1| last = Ibn Ishaq| others = A. Guillaume (trans.)| title = The Life of Muhammad| date = 2004|quote=They went on their way as far as Ma\u2018\u0101n in Syria where they heard that Heraclius had come down to Ma\u2019\u0101b in the Balq\u0101\u02be with 100,000 Greeks joined by 100,000 men from Lakhm and Judh\u0101m and al-Qayn and Bahr\u0101\u02be and Bal\u012b commanded by a man of Bal\u012b of Ir\u0101sha called M\u0101lik b. Z\u0101fila.| page=532}}</ref><br>{{small|(both exaggerated)}}{{sfn|Haldon|2010|p=188}}{{sfn|Peters|1994|p=231}}{{sfn|Buhl|1993|p=756-757}}\n10,000 or fewer {{small|(modern estimate)}}{{sfn|Kaegi|1992|p=79}}\n| casualties1       = 12<ref name=zayd>{{Cite book| publisher = University of Pennsylvania Press| isbn = 978-0-8122-4617-9| last = Powers| first = David S.| title = Zayd| date = 2014-05-23|pages=58\u20139}}</ref> {{small|(Disputed)}}{{sfn|Peterson|2007|p=142}}{{sfn|Powers|2009|p=80}}\n| casualties2       = Unknown\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Campaigns of Muhammad}}\n{{Campaignbox Arab\u2013Byzantine Wars}}\n{{Campaignbox Campaigns of Khalid ibn Walid}}\n{{History of Jordan}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Mu'tah''' ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u064e\u0639\u0652\u0631\u064e\u0643\u064e\u0629 \u0645\u064f\u0624\u0652\u062a\u064e\u0629}} ''{{transl|ar|Ma\u02bfrakah Mu\u02bftah}}'', or {{lang-ar|\u063a\u064e\u0632\u0652\u0648\u064e\u0629 \u0645\u064f\u0624\u0652\u062a\u064e\u0629|link=no}} ''{{transl|ar|Ghazwah Mu\u02bftah|link=no}}'') was fought in September 629 [[Common Era|CE]] (1 [[Jumada al-Awwal]] 8 [[Hijri year|AH]]),{{sfn| Kaegi|1992|p=72}} near the village of [[Mu'tah]], east of the [[Jordan River]] and [[Al Karak|Karak]] in [[Karak Governorate]], between the forces of the Islamic prophet [[Muhammad]] and the forces of the [[Byzantine Empire]] and their [[Arab Christian]] [[Ghassanid]] vassals.\n\nIn Islamic historical sources, the battle is usually described as the Muslims' attempt to take retribution against a Ghassanid chief for taking the life of an emissary. According to Byzantine sources, the Muslims planned to launch their attack on a feast day. The local Byzantine [[Vicarius]] learned of their plans and collected the garrisons of the fortresses. Seeing the great number of the enemy forces, the Muslims withdrew to the south where the fighting started at the village of Mu'ta and they were routed.{{sfn|Buhl|1993|p=756-757}}{{sfn|Kaegi|1992|p=67}} According to Muslim sources, after three of their leaders were killed, the command was given to [[Khalid ibn al-Walid]] and he succeeded in saving the rest of the force.{{sfn|Buhl|1993|p=756-757}}\n\n==Background==\nThe Byzantines were reoccupying territory following the peace accord between Emperor [[Heraclius]] and the [[Shahrbaraz|Sasanid general Shahrbaraz]] in July 629.{{sfn|Kaegi|1992|p=72-73}} The Byzantine ''[[sakellarios]]'' Theodore,{{sfn|Kaegi|1992|p=35}} was placed in command of the army, and while in the area of Balqa, Arab tribes were also employed.{{sfn|Kaegi|1992|p=72-73}}\n\nMeanwhile, Muhammad had sent his emissary to the ruler of Bosra.{{sfn|El Hareir|M'Baye|2011|p=142}} While on his way to Bosra, he was executed in the village of Mu'tah by the orders of a Ghassanid official.{{sfn|El Hareir|M'Baye|2011|p=142}}\n\n==Mobilization of the armies==\nMuhammad dispatched 3,000 of his troops in the month of [[Jumada al-Awwal]] 7 (AH), 629 (CE), for a quick expedition to attack and punish the tribes for the murder of his emissary by the Ghassanids.{{sfn|El Hareir|M'Baye|2011|p=142}} The army was led by [[Zayd ibn Harithah]]; the second-in-command was [[Ja'far ibn Abi Talib]] and the third-in-command was [[Abd Allah ibn Rawahah]]. When the Muslim troops arrived at the area to the east of Jordan and learned of the size of the Byzantine army, they wanted to wait and send for reinforcements from [[Medina]]. 'Abdullah ibn Rawahah reminded them about their desire for martyrdom and questioned the move to wait when what they desire was awaiting them, so they continued marching towards the waiting army.\n\n==The battle==\nThe Muslims engaged the Byzantines at their camp by the village of Musharif and then withdrew towards Mu'tah. It was here that the two armies fought. Some Muslim sources report that the battle was fought in a valley between two heights, which negated the Byzantines' numerical superiority. During the battle, all three Muslim leaders fell one after the other as they took command of the force: first, Zayd, then Ja'far, then 'Abdullah. After the death of the latter, some of the Muslim soldiers began to rout. Thabit ibn Al-Arqam, seeing the desperate state of the Muslim forces, took up the banner and rallied his comrades thus saving the army from complete destruction. After the battle, Al-Arqam took the banner, before asking [[Khalid ibn al-Walid]] to take the lead.<ref name=\"Al-Islam Ja'far\">{{citation |publisher=[[Ahlul Bayt Digital Islamic Library Project|Al-Islam.org]] |title=Jafar al-Tayyar |url=http://www.al-islam.org/jafar-al-tayyar-kamal-al-sayyid/jafar-al-tayyar/ |access-date=}}</ref>\n\nKhalid bin Walid reported that the fighting at Mu'tah was so intense that he used nine swords which broke during the battle. Khalid, seeing that the situation was hopeless, prepared to withdraw. He continued to engage the Byzantines in skirmishes, but avoided pitched battle.\n\n==Muslim losses==\nThe casualties of slain of the Muslim side were recorded as the four of them from [[Muhajireen]] while eight the rest from [[Ansar (Islam)|Ansar]]. Their names were:\n# [[Zayd ibn Harithah]]\n# [[Ja'far ibn Abi Talib]] \n# [[Abd Allah ibn Rawahah]] \n# Masoud bin Al-Aswad\n# Wahab bin Saad \n# Abbad bin Qais \n# Amr ibn Saad (not [[Umar ibn Sa'ad|Sa'd ibn Abi Waqqas's son]])\n# Harith bin Nu'man\n# Saraqah bin Amr \n# Abu Kulaib bin Amr\n# Jabir ibn 'Amr \n# Amer bin Saad\n\nDaniel C. Peterson, Professor of Islamic Studies at Brigham Young University, finds the ratio of casualties among the leaders suspiciously high compared to the losses suffered by ordinary soldiers.{{sfn|Peterson|2007|p=142}} David Powers, Professor of Near Eastern Studies at Cornell, also mentions this curiosity concerning the minuscule casualties recorded by Muslim historians.{{sfn|Powers|2009|p=80}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nIt is reported that when the Muslim force arrived at Medina, they were berated for withdrawing and accused of fleeing.{{sfn|Powers|2009|p=81}} Salamah ibn Hisham, brother of [[Amr ibn Hish\u0101m]] (Abu Jahl) was reported to have prayed at home rather than going to the mosque to avoid having to explain himself. Muhammad ordered them to stop, saying that they would return to fight the Byzantines again.{{sfn|Powers|2009|p=81}} It would not be until the third century AH that Sunni Muslim historians would state that Muhammad bestowed upon Khalid the title of 'Saifullah' meaning 'Sword of Allah'.{{sfn|Powers|2009|p=80}}\n\nToday, Muslims who fell at the battle are considered [[martyr]]s (''[[shahid|shuhad\u0101\u02be]]'').{{cn|date=January 2020}} A [[mausoleum]] was later built at Mu'tah over their graves.{{sfn|Buhl|1993|p=756-757}}\n\n==Historiography ==\nAccording to [[al-Waqidi]] and [[Ibn Ishaq]], the Muslims were informed that 100,000<ref name=waqidi /> or 200,000<ref name=ishaq/> enemy troops were encamped at [[Balqa]]'.<ref name=waqidi />{{sfn|Haykal|1976|p=419}} Consequently, modern historians refute this stating the figure to be exaggerated.{{sfn|Haldon|2010|p=188}}{{sfn|Peters|1994|p=231}}{{sfn|Buhl|1993|p=756-757}} According to Walter Emil Kaegi, professor of Byzantine history at the [[University of Chicago]], the size of the entire Byzantine army during the 7th century might have totaled 100,000, possibly even half this number.{{sfn|Kaegi|2010|p=99}} While the Byzantine forces at Mu'tah are unlikely to have numbered more than 10,000.{{efn|The Byzantines do not appear to have used many Greek, Armenian, or other non-Arab soldiers at Mu'ta, even though the overall commander was the ''vicarius'' Theodore. The number that the Byzantines raised are, of course, uncertain, but unlikely to have exceeded 10,000.{{sfn|Kaegi|1992|p=79}}}}{{sfn|Kaegi|1992|p=79}}\n\nMuslim accounts of the battle differ over the result.{{sfn|Powers|2009|p=80}} In the earliest Muslim sources, the battle is recorded as a humiliating defeat. (''haz\u012bma'').{{sfn|Powers|2009|p=80}} Later Muslim historians reworked the early source material to reflect the Islamic view of God's plan.{{sfn|Powers|2009|p=80}} Subsequent sources present the battle as a Muslim victory given that most of the Muslim soldiers returned safely.{{sfn|Powers|2009|p=80}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Battle of Mu'tah}}\n*[[Military career of Muhammad]]\n*[[List of expeditions of Muhammad]]\n*[[History of Islam]]\n*[[Military career of Muhammad]]\n*[[Jihad]]\n*[[Muhammad's views on Christians]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book |title=The Different Aspects of Islam Culture: Volume 3, The Spread of Islam throughout the World |last1=El Hareir |first1=Idris |last2=M'Baye |first2=El Hadji Ravane |publisher=UNESCO publishing |year=2011 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia | editor =H. A. R. Gibb | first = F. | last = Buhl | editorlink = H. A. R. Gibb | encyclopedia = Encyclopaedia of Islam | isbn = 9789004094192 | title = Mu\u02beta| edition = Second | year = 1993 | publisher = BRILL | volume = 7 | ref=harv| page=756}}\n*{{cite book |title=Money, Power and Politics in Early Islamic Syria |last=Haldon |first=John |publisher=Ashgate Publishing |year=2010 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |title=The Life of Muhammad |last=Haykal |first=Muhammad |publisher=Islamic Book Trust |year=1976 |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book| url = http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IvPVEb17uzkC| title = Byzantium and the Early Islamic Conquests| last = Kaegi| first = Walter E.| publisher = Cambridge University Press| year = 1992| isbn = 978-0521411721|location = Cambridge| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book |title=Muslim Expansion and Byzantine Collapse in North Africa |last=Kaegi |first=Walter E. |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2010 |ISBN=978-0-521-19677-2 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |title=Muhammad and the Origins of Islam  |url=https://archive.org/details/muhammadorigins00pete |url-access=registration |last=Peters |first=Francis E. |publisher=State University of New York Press |year=1994 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |title=Muhammad, Prophet of God |last=Peterson |first=Daniel C. |publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing Co. |year=2007 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |title=Muhammad Is Not the Father of Any of Your Men: The Making of the Last Prophet |last=Powers |first=David S. |publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press |year=2009 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |title=A Global Chronology of Conflict |volume=Vol. I |editor-last=Tucker |editor-first=Spencer |publisher=ABC-CLIO |year=2010 |ref=harv}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[http://www.archive.org/details/TheSealedNectar_201802 ''Ar-Raheeq Al-Makhtum'' (The Sealed Nectar)]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061231061738/http://www.witness-pioneer.org/vil/Books/MH_LM/campaign_of_mutah.htm The Life of Muhammad]\n*[http://drive.google.com/drive/folders/0B2NPAUkyo-6wfnpWaW9tVi13YlMzcmprRTNYQ3B0OXIzRGFXMy1kclE1dmtvS2JTLWl6RTA Ikoalag Historical]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080303102120/http://www.grandestrategy.com/2007/12/sword-of-allah-chapter-6-mutah-and.html Sword of Allah]\n\n{{coord missing|Jordan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Battle Of Mu'tah}}\n[[Category:629]]\n[[Category:620s in the Byzantine Empire]]\n[[Category:Campaigns ordered by Muhammad|Mu'tah]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Byzantine Empire|Mu'tah]]\n[[Category:Battles of Khalid ibn Walid|Mu'tah]]\n[[Category:Battles of the Arab\u2013Byzantine wars|Mu'tah]]\n[[Category:Medieval Jordan]]\n[[Category:Battles of Muhammad|Mu'tah]]\n[[Category:620s conflicts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict          = Battle of Mu'tah<br>{{lang|ar|\u063a\u064e\u0632\u0652\u0648\u064e\u0629 \u0645\u064f\u0624\u0652\u062a\u064e\u0629}}<br>{{lang|ar|\u0645\u064e\u0639\u0652\u0631\u064e\u0643\u064e\u0629 \u0645\u064f\u0624\u0652\u062a\u064e\u0629}}\n| partof            = the [[Arab\u2013Byzantine wars]]\n| image             = Mausoleum ,Jafer-ut-Tayyar,Jordan.JPG\n| caption           = The tomb of Muslim commanders [[Zayd ibn Harithah]], [[Ja'far ibn Abi Talib]], and [[Abd Allah ibn Rawahah]] in Al-Mazar near [[Mu'tah]], [[Jordan]]\n| next_battle       = [[Battle of Yarmouk]]\n| date              = September 629{{sfn|Kaegi|1992|p=72}}\n| place             = [[Mu'tah]], [[Karak Governorate]], [[Jordan]], [[Syria (region)|Sham]]\n| result            = Byzantine victory{{sfn|Kaegi|1992|p=67}}{{sfn|Tucker|2010|p=200}}\n| combatant1        = [[Muslim conquests|Muslim Arabs]]\n| combatant2        = [[File:Simple_Labarum2.svg|15px]] [[Byzantine Empire]]<br>[[Ghassanids]]\n| commander1        = [[Zayd ibn Harithah]]{{KIA}}<br>[[Ja'far ibn Abi Talib]]{{KIA}}<br>[[Abd Allah ibn Rawahah]]{{KIA}}<br><ref name=zayd /> [[Khalid ibn Al-Walid]]\n| commander2        = [[Theodore (brother of Heraclius)|Theodore]]<br>[[Heraclius]]<br>[[Shurahbil ibn Amr]]\n| strength1         = 3,000{{sfn|Powers|2009|p=86}}\n| strength2         = 100,000 ([[Al-Waqidi]])<ref name=waqidi>{{Cite book| publisher = Cambridge University Press| isbn = 978-0-521-59984-9| last = Gil| first = Moshe| title = A History of Palestine, 634-1099| date = 1997-02-27|page=23}}</ref><br>200,000 ([[Ibn Ishaq]])<ref name=ishaq>{{Cite book| publisher = Oxford University Press, USA| isbn = 0-19-636033-1| last = Ibn Ishaq| others = A. Guillaume (trans.)| title = The Life of Muhammad| date = 2004|quote=They went on their way as far as Ma\u2018\u0101n in Syria where they heard that Heraclius had come down to Ma\u2019\u0101b in the Balq\u0101\u02be with 100,000 Greeks joined by 100,000 men from Lakhm and Judh\u0101m and al-Qayn and Bahr\u0101\u02be and Bal\u012b commanded by a man of Bal\u012b of Ir\u0101sha called M\u0101lik b. Z\u0101fila.| page=532}}</ref><br>{{small|(both exaggerated)}}{{sfn|Haldon|2010|p=188}}{{sfn|Peters|1994|p=231}}{{sfn|Buhl|1993|p=756-757}}\n10,000 or fewer {{small|(modern estimate)}}{{sfn|Kaegi|1992|p=79}}\n| casualties1       = 12<ref name=zayd>{{Cite book| publisher = University of Pennsylvania Press| isbn = 978-0-8122-4617-9| last = Powers| first = David S.| title = Zayd| date = 2014-05-23|pages=58\u20139}}</ref> {{small|(Disputed)}}{{sfn|Peterson|2007|p=142}}{{sfn|Powers|2009|p=80}}\n| casualties2       = Unknown\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Campaigns of Muhammad}}\n{{Campaignbox Arab\u2013Byzantine Wars}}\n{{Campaignbox Campaigns of Khalid ibn Walid}}\n{{History of Jordan}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Mu'tah''' ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u064e\u0639\u0652\u0631\u064e\u0643\u064e\u0629 \u0645\u064f\u0624\u0652\u062a\u064e\u0629}} ''{{transl|ar|Ma\u02bfrakah Mu\u02bftah}}'', or {{lang-ar|\u063a\u064e\u0632\u0652\u0648\u064e\u0629 \u0645\u064f\u0624\u0652\u062a\u064e\u0629|link=no}} ''{{transl|ar|Ghazwah Mu\u02bftah|link=no}}'') was fought in September 629 [[Common Era|CE]] (1 [[Jumada al-Awwal]] 8 [[Hijri year|AH]]),{{sfn| Kaegi|1992|p=72}} near the village of [[Mu'tah]], east of the [[Jordan River]] and [[Al Karak|Karak]] in [[Karak Governorate]], between the forces of the Islamic prophet [[Muhammad]] and the forces of the [[Byzantine Empire]] and their [[Arab Christian]] [[Ghassanid]] vassals.\n\nIn Islamic historical sources, the battle is usually described as the Muslims' attempt to take retribution against a Ghassanid chief for taking the life of an emissary. According to Byzantine sources, the Muslims planned to launch their attack on a feast day. The local Byzantine [[Vicarius]] learned of their plans and collected the garrisons of the fortresses. Seeing the great number of the enemy forces, the Muslims withdrew to the south where the fighting started at the village of Mu'ta and they were routed.{{sfn|Buhl|1993|p=756-757}}{{sfn|Kaegi|1992|p=67}} According to Muslim sources, after three of their leaders were killed, the command was given to [[Khalid ibn al-Walid]] and he succeeded in saving the rest of the force.{{sfn|Buhl|1993|p=756-757}}\n\n==Background==\nThe Byzantines were reoccupying territory following the peace accord between Emperor [[Heraclius]] and the [[Shahrbaraz|Sasanid general Shahrbaraz]] in July 629.{{sfn|Kaegi|1992|p=72-73}} The Byzantine ''[[sakellarios]]'' Theodore,{{sfn|Kaegi|1992|p=35}} was placed in command of the army, and while in the area of Balqa, Arab tribes were also employed.{{sfn|Kaegi|1992|p=72-73}}\n\nMeanwhile, Muhammad had sent his emissary to the ruler of Bosra.{{sfn|El Hareir|M'Baye|2011|p=142}} While on his way to Bosra, he was executed in the village of Mu'tah by the orders of a Ghassanid official.{{sfn|El Hareir|M'Baye|2011|p=142}}\n\n==Mobilization of the armies==\nMuhammad dispatched 3,000 of his troops in the month of [[Jumada al-Awwal]] 7 (AH), 629 (CE), for a quick expedition to attack and punish the tribes for the murder of his emissary by the Ghassanids.{{sfn|El Hareir|M'Baye|2011|p=142}} The army was led by [[Zayd ibn Harithah]]; the second-in-command was [[Ja'far ibn Abi Talib]] and the third-in-command was [[Abd Allah ibn Rawahah]]. When the Muslim troops arrived at the area to the east of Jordan and learned of the size of the Byzantine army, they wanted to wait and send for reinforcements from [[Medina]]. 'Abdullah ibn Rawahah reminded them about their desire for martyrdom and questioned the move to wait when what they desire was awaiting them, so they continued marching towards the waiting army.\n\n==The battle==\nThe Muslims engaged the Byzantines at their camp by the village of Musharif and then withdrew towards Mu'tah. It was here that the two armies fought. Some Muslim sources report that the battle was fought in a valley between two heights, which negated the Byzantines' numerical superiority. During the battle, all three Muslim leaders fell one after the other as they took command of the force: first, Zayd, then Ja'far, then 'Abdullah. After the death of the latter, some of the Muslim soldiers began to rout. Thabit ibn Al-Arqam, seeing the desperate state of the Muslim forces, took up the banner and rallied his comrades thus saving the army from complete destruction. After the battle, Al-Arqam took the banner, before asking [[Khalid ibn al-Walid]] to take the lead.<ref name=\"Al-Islam Ja'far\">{{citation |publisher=[[Ahlul Bayt Digital Islamic Library Project|Al-Islam.org]] |title=Jafar al-Tayyar |url=http://www.al-islam.org/jafar-al-tayyar-kamal-al-sayyid/jafar-al-tayyar/ |access-date=}}</ref>\n\nKhalid bin Walid reported that the fighting at Mu'tah was so intense that he used nine swords which broke during the battle. Khalid, seeing that the situation was hopeless, prepared to withdraw. He continued to engage the Byzantines in skirmishes, but avoided pitched battle.\n\n==Muslim losses==\nThe casualties of slain of the Muslim side were recorded as the four of them from [[Muhajireen]] while eight the rest from [[Ansar (Islam)|Ansar]]. Their names were:\n# [[Zayd ibn Harithah]]\n# [[Ja'far ibn Abi Talib]] \n# [[Abd Allah ibn Rawahah]] \n# Masoud bin Al-Aswad\n# Wahab bin Saad \n# Abbad bin Qais \n# Amr ibn Saad (not [[Umar ibn Sa'ad|Sa'd ibn Abi Waqqas's son]])\n# Harith bin Nu'man\n# Saraqah bin Amr \n# Abu Kulaib bin Amr\n# Jabir ibn 'Amr \n# Amer bin Saad\n\nDaniel C. Peterson, Professor of Islamic Studies at Brigham Young University, finds the ratio of casualties among the leaders suspiciously high compared to the losses suffered by ordinary soldiers.{{sfn|Peterson|2007|p=142}} David Powers, Professor of Near Eastern Studies at Cornell, also mentions this curiosity concerning the minuscule casualties recorded by Muslim historians.{{sfn|Powers|2009|p=80}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nIt is reported that when the Muslim force arrived at Medina, they were berated for withdrawing and accused of fleeing.{{sfn|Powers|2009|p=81}} Salamah ibn Hisham, brother of [[Amr ibn Hish\u0101m]] (Abu Jahl) was reported to have prayed at home rather than going to the mosque to avoid having to explain himself. Muhammad ordered them to stop, saying that they would return to fight the Byzantines again.{{sfn|Powers|2009|p=81}} It would not be until the third century AH that Sunni Muslim historians would state that Muhammad bestowed upon Khalid the title of 'Saifullah' meaning 'Sword of Allah'.{{sfn|Powers|2009|p=80}}\n\nToday, Muslims who fell at the battle are considered [[martyr]]s (''[[shahid|shuhad\u0101\u02be]]'').{{cn|date=January 2020}} A [[mausoleum]] was later built at Mu'tah over their graves.{{sfn|Buhl|1993|p=756-757}}\n\n==Historiography ==\nAccording to [[al-Waqidi]] and [[Ibn Ishaq]], the Muslims were informed that 100,000<ref name=waqidi /> or 200,000<ref name=ishaq/> enemy troops were encamped at [[Balqa]]'.<ref name=waqidi />{{sfn|Haykal|1976|p=419}} Consequently, modern historians refute this stating the figure to be exaggerated.{{sfn|Haldon|2010|p=188}}{{sfn|Peters|1994|p=231}}{{sfn|Buhl|1993|p=756-757}} According to Walter Emil Kaegi, professor of Byzantine history at the [[University of Chicago]], the size of the entire Byzantine army during the 7th century might have totaled 100,000, possibly even half this number.{{sfn|Kaegi|2010|p=99}} While the Byzantine forces at Mu'tah are unlikely to have numbered more than 10,000.{{efn|The Byzantines do not appear to have used many Greek, Armenian, or other non-Arab soldiers at Mu'ta, even though the overall commander was the ''vicarius'' Theodore. The number that the Byzantines raised are, of course, uncertain, but unlikely to have exceeded 10,000.{{sfn|Kaegi|1992|p=79}}}}{{sfn|Kaegi|1992|p=79}}\n\nMuslim accounts of the battle differ over the result.{{sfn|Powers|2009|p=80}} In the earliest Muslim sources, the battle is recorded as a humiliating defeat. (''haz\u012bma'').{{sfn|Powers|2009|p=80}} Later Muslim historians reworked the early source material to reflect the Islamic view of God's plan.{{sfn|Powers|2009|p=80}} Subsequent sources present the battle as a Muslim victory given that most of the Muslim soldiers returned safely.{{sfn|Powers|2009|p=80}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category|Battle of Mu'tah}}\n*[[Military career of Muhammad]]\n*[[List of expeditions of Muhammad]]\n*[[History of Islam]]\n*[[Military career of Muhammad]]\n*[[Jihad]]\n*[[Muhammad's views on Christians]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book |title=The Different Aspects of Islam Culture: Volume 3, The Spread of Islam throughout the World |last1=El Hareir |first1=Idris |last2=M'Baye |first2=El Hadji Ravane |publisher=UNESCO publishing |year=2011 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite encyclopedia | editor =H. A. R. Gibb | first = F. | last = Buhl | editorlink = H. A. R. Gibb | encyclopedia = Encyclopaedia of Islam | isbn = 9789004094192 | title = Mu\u02beta| edition = Second | year = 1993 | publisher = BRILL | volume = 7 | ref=harv| page=756}}\n*{{cite book |title=Money, Power and Politics in Early Islamic Syria |last=Haldon |first=John |publisher=Ashgate Publishing |year=2010 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |title=The Life of Muhammad |last=Haykal |first=Muhammad |publisher=Islamic Book Trust |year=1976 |ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book| url = http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IvPVEb17uzkC| title = Byzantium and the Early Islamic Conquests| last = Kaegi| first = Walter E.| publisher = Cambridge University Press| year = 1992| isbn = 978-0521411721|location = Cambridge| ref = harv}}\n*{{cite book |title=Muslim Expansion and Byzantine Collapse in North Africa |last=Kaegi |first=Walter E. |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2010 |ISBN=978-0-521-19677-2 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |title=Muhammad and the Origins of Islam  |url=https://archive.org/details/muhammadorigins00pete |url-access=registration |last=Peters |first=Francis E. |publisher=State University of New York Press |year=1994 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |title=Muhammad, Prophet of God |last=Peterson |first=Daniel C. |publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing 