{"title_page": "The Secret Life of Nora", "text_new": "\n\n\n'''''The Secret Life of Nora''''' was staged at the Malaysian National Theatre, [[Istana Budaya]] from 29th Sept - 16th Oct 2011, and performed in [[Malaysian language|Bahasa Malaysia]] and English. Produced by [https://www.enfiniti.com.my/ EnfinitiMy] with [[Tiara Jacquelina]] as Executive Producer, story by Raymond Miranda, music composed by Weng Onn San, lyrics written by Jerome Kugan with Alfian Sa'at and [[Mamat Khalid]], music by Roslan Aziz, directed by [[Steven Dexter]], choreographed by Pat Ibrahim. \n\nNora (played by multi-award winning Malaysian actress [[Tiara Jacquelina]]), the prima donna of a Malaysian cabaret, who is tricked into becoming a spy to help uncover a mysterious evil plot by an evil baddie, Mr J (played by award-winning TV Host [[Aznil Nawawi]]). Along the way, she falls in love with Roger Foss (Broadway star Ryan Silverman - Chicago, Passion, Side Show, Phantom Of The Opera), an international agent who helps transform her from Drama Queen to a skilled undercover spy! Nora\u2019s roller-coaster of a journey is one of high adventure, love, comedic moments as well as tears, deception, self-doubt & ultimately, self-empowerment.\n\nThe Secret Life of Nora won several awards at the 9th BOH Cameronian Arts Awards 2012, including Kakiseni Audience Choice Awards for Musical Theatre, Best Original Book And/Or Lyrics (Raymond Miranda, Mamat Khalid, Elliot Davis, Steven Dexter and Alfian Sa\u2019at) and Best Performance In A Supporting Role (Stephanie Van Driesen)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Secret Life of Nora}}\n[[Category:2011 musicals]]\n[[Category:Malaysian musicals]]\n\n\n{{musical-theatre-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical\n| name        = The Secret Life of Nora\n| image       = \n| image_size  = 200px\n| Producer    = [[Tiara Jacquelina]]\n| music       = Weng Onn San\n| lyrics      = [[Jerome Kugan]] with Alfian Sa\u2019at ([[Bahasa Malaysia]] lyrics)\n| book        = Raymond Miranda\n| basis       = 1965 film by [[Low Wai]]{{br}}''[[:ms:Filem Nora Zain - Agen Wanita 001|Nora Zain - Agen Wanita 001]]''\n| productions = 2011 Kuala Lumpur\n| awards      = None\n}}\n'''''The Secret Life of Nora''''' is a [[Malaysia]]n musical.<ref name=\"stagekl\">{{cite web|url=http://stagekl.com/shows/the-secret-life-of-nora/|title=StageKL - The Secret Life of Nora|publisher=stagekl.com|accessdate=2016-07-25}}</ref> The booklet was written by Raymond Miranda,<ref name=\"asiaone\">{{cite web|url=http://news.asiaone.com/News/Latest%2BNews/Showbiz/Story/A1Story20110614-283910.html|title=Bond with Nora the secret agent|publisher=news.asiaone.com|accessdate=2016-07-25}}</ref> the music was composed by Weng Onn San<ref name=\"asiaone\"/> and the lyrics were written by [[Jerome Kugan]]<ref name=\"asiaone\"/> with Alfian Sa\u2019at (for the [[Bahasa Malaysia]] text).<ref name=\"stagekl2\">{{cite web|url=http://stagekl.com/shows/the-secret-life-of-nora/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718105641/http://stagekl.com/shows/the-secret-life-of-nora/|archive-date=2011-07-18|url-status=dead|title=StageKL - The Secret Life of Nora|accessdate=2016-07-25}}</ref> The first stage performance was directed by [[Steven Dexter]] and premiered at the [[Istana Budaya]] on September, 29th 2011.<ref name=\"asiaone\"/>\n\nSet in a whimsical version of Penang, The Secret Life of Nora stars [[Tiara Jacquelina]] in the titular role as a beautiful, rich, spoiled cabaret owner and singer. Nora has a brush of trouble with Interpol after the death of her father reveals the cabaret to be a front for his illegal international business activities. Stuck in a tight spot, Nora accepts a proposition from Interpol to masquerade as a spy and infiltrate one of the biggest human trafficking rings in the world in exchange for her freedom and to save her beloved cabaret.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Secret Life of Nora}}\n[[Category:2011 musicals]]\n[[Category:Malaysian musicals]]\n\n\n{{musical-theatre-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Sh33la", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Secret_Life_of_Nora"}
{"title_page": "Skull fracture", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| name            = Skull fracture \n| image           = Depressed skull fracture.jpg \n| caption         = A piece of a [[skull]] with a depressed skull fracture \n| pronounce       =  \n| field           =  \n| synonyms        =  \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n\nA '''skull fracture''' is a break in one or more of the eight bones that form the cranial portion of the [[human skull|skull]], usually occurring as a result of [[blunt force trauma]].  If the force of the impact is excessive, the [[bone]] may fracture at or near the site of the impact and cause damage to the underlying structures within the skull such as the [[Meninges|membranes]], [[blood vessel]]s, and [[Human brain|brain]].\n\nWhile an uncomplicated skull fracture can occur without associated  physical or [[neurological]] damage and is in itself usually not clinically significant, a fracture in healthy bone indicates that a substantial amount of force has been applied and increases the possibility of associated [[traumatic brain injury|injury]]. Any significant blow to the head results in a [[concussion]], with or without loss of [[consciousness]].\n\nA fracture in conjunction with an overlying [[laceration]] that tears the [[epidermis (skin)|epidermis]] and the [[meninges]], or runs through the [[paranasal sinuses]] and the [[middle ear]] structures, bringing the outside environment into contact with the cranial cavity is called a compound fracture. Compound fractures can either be clean or contaminated.\n\nThere are four major types of skull fractures: linear, depressed, diastatic, and basilar. Linear fractures are the most common, and usually require no intervention for the fracture itself. Depressed fractures are usually [[Bone fracture|comminuted]], with broken portions of bone displaced inward\u2014and may require surgical intervention to repair underlying tissue damage. Diastatic fractures widen the sutures of the skull and usually affect children under three. Basilar fractures are in the bones at the base of the skull.\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n==Types==\n\n===Linear fracture===\nLinear skull fractures are breaks in the bone that transverse the full thickness of the skull from the outer to inner table. They are usually fairly straight with no bone displacement. The common cause of injury is blunt force trauma where the impact energy transferred over a wide area of the skull.\n\nLinear skull fractures are usually of little clinical significance unless they parallel in close proximity or transverse a [[Suture (joint)|suture]], or they involve a venous sinus groove or vascular channel. The resulting complications may include suture [[diastasis (pathology)|diastasis]], [[venous sinus thrombosis]], and [[epidural hematoma]]. In young children, although rare, the possibility exists of developing a growing skull fracture especially if the fracture occurs in the [[parietal bone]].<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 1190143 | volume=129 | title=Complication of linear skull fracture in young children | date=October 1975 | author=Haar FL | journal=Am. J. Dis. Child. | pages=1197\u2013200 }}</ref>\n\n===Depressed fracture===\n[[File:Depressed skull fracture2.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Depressed skull fracture.]]\nA depressed skull fracture is a type of fracture usually resulting from blunt force trauma, such as getting struck with a hammer, rock or getting kicked in the head. These types of fractures\u2014which occur in 11% of severe head injuries\u2014are comminuted fractures in which broken bones displace inward. Depressed skull fractures present a high risk of increased [[intracranial pressure|pressure on the brain]], or a hemorrhage to the brain that crushes the delicate tissue.\n\nCompound depressed skull fractures occur when there is a laceration over the fracture, putting the internal cranial cavity in contact with the outside environment, increasing the risk of contamination and infection. In complex depressed fractures, the [[dura mater]] is torn. Depressed skull fractures may require [[neurosurgery|surgery]] to lift the bones off the brain if they are pressing on it by making burr holes on the adjacent normal skull.<ref name=\"singh\">Singh J and Stock A. 2006. [http://www.emedicine.com/ped/topic929.htm \"Head Trauma.\"] Emedicine.com. Retrieved on January 26, 2007.</ref>\n\n===Diastatic fracture===\n[[File:Cleidocranial2.jpg|thumb|right|180px|cranial abnormalities in cleidocranial dysplasia including diastatic sutures.]]\nDiastatic fractures occur when the fracture line transverses\none or more sutures of the skull causing a widening of the suture. While this type of fracture is usually seen in infants and young children as the sutures are not yet fused it can also occur in adults. When a diastatic fracture occurs in adults it usually affects the [[lambdoidal suture]] as this suture does not fully fuse in adults until about the age of 60. Other than that Most adult diastatic fractures are caused by severe head injuries. Due to the trauma, diastatic fracture occurs with the collapse of the surrounding head bones. It makes the delicate tissue to be crushed, like depressed skull fracture.\n\nDiastatic fractures can occur with different types of fractures and it is also possible for diastasis of the cranial sutures to occur without a concomitant  fracture. Sutural diastasis may also occur in various congenital disorders such as [[cleidocranial dysplasia]] and [[osteogenesis imperfecta]].<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 8456801 | doi=10.1002/ajmg.1320450208 | volume=45 | title=Osteogenesis imperfecta: the distinction from child abuse and the recognition of a variant form | date=January 1993 | author=Paterson CR, Burns J, McAllion SJ | journal=Am. J. Med. Genet. | pages=187\u201392 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 9430147 | volume=25 | title=[Cleidocranial dysplasia: a case report] | date=December 1997 | author=Kanda M, Kabe S, Kanki T, Sato J, Hasegawa Y | journal=No Shinkei Geka | pages=1109\u201313 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 17122029 | volume=106 | title=Significance of differences in patency among cranial sutures | date=October 2006 | author=Sabini RC, Elkowitz DE | journal=J Am Osteopath Assoc | pages=600\u20134 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 18216661 | doi=10.1097/SCS.0b013e31815ca07a | volume=19 | title=Definition of topographic organization of skull profile in normal population and its implications on the role of sutures in skull morphology | date=January 2008 | author=Pirouzmand F, Muhajarine N | journal=J Craniofac Surg | pages=27\u201336 }}</ref>\n\n===Basilar fracture===\n{{main|Basilar skull fracture}}\n[[File:Sch\u00e4delbasis1.jpg|thumb|130px|Superior view of the skull base.]]\n[[Basilar skull fracture]]s are linear fractures that occur in the floor of the cranial vault (skull base), which require more force to cause than other areas of the neurocranium. Thus they are rare, occurring as the only fracture in only 4% of severe head injury patients.\n\nBasilar fractures have characteristic signs: blood in the [[Paranasal sinus|sinuses]]; a clear fluid called [[cerebrospinal fluid]] (CSF) leaking from the nose ([[rhinorrhea]]) or ears ([[otorrhea]]); [[periorbital]] [[ecchymosis]]  often called '[[raccoon eyes]]'<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 11754879 | volume=32 | title='Raccoon eyes' (periorbital haematoma) as a sign of skull base fracture | date=December 2001 | author=Herbella FA, Mudo M, Delmonti C, Braga FM, Del Grande JC | journal=Injury | pages=745\u20137 }}</ref> (bruising of the orbits of the eyes that result from blood collecting there as it leaks from the fracture site); and retro[[Ear|auricular]] ecchymosis known as \"[[Battle's sign]]\" (bruising over the mastoid process).<ref>{{cite journal | author = Tubbs RS, Shoja MM, Loukas M | display-authors = etal | date = Jan 2010 | title = William Henry Battle and Battle's sign: mastoid ecchymosis as an indicator of basilar skull fracture | url = | journal = J Neurosurg | volume = 112 | issue = 1| pages = 186\u20138 | pmid = 19392601 | doi = 10.3171/2008.8.JNS08241 }}</ref>\n\n===Growing fracture===\nA growing skull fracture (GSF) also known as a craniocerebral erosion or leptomeningeal cyst<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 20496339 | volume=29 | title=Leptomeningeal cyst in a child after head trauma: a case report | year=2010 | author=Irabor PF, Akhigbe AO | journal=West Afr J Med | pages=44\u20136 }}</ref> due to the usual development of a cystic mass filled with cerebrospinal fluid  is a rare complication of head injury usually associated with linear skull fractures of the parietal bone in children under 3. It has been reported in older children in atypical regions of the skull such as the basiooccipital and the base of the skull base and in association with other types of skull fractures. It is characterized by a diastatic enlargement of the fracture.\n\nVarious factors are associated with the development of a GSF. The primary causitive factor is a tear in the [[dura mater]]. The skull fracture enlarges due, in part, to the rapid physiologic growth of the brain that occurs in young children, and brain [[cerebrospinal fluid]] (CSF) pulsations in the underlying [[Leptomeninges|leptomenigeal]] [[cyst]]ic mass.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 9401652 | volume=139 | title=Growing skull fractures: a clinical study of 41 patients | year=1997 | author=Gupta SK, Reddy NM, Khosla VK | display-authors = etal | journal=Acta Neurochir (Wien) | pages=928\u201332 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 11086738 | volume=23 | title=Growing skull fractures (craniocerebral erosion) | date=September 2000 | author=Ersahin Y, G\u00fclmen V, Palali I, Mutluer S | journal=Neurosurg Rev | pages=139\u201344 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 7792708 | volume=43 | title=Pathogenesis and treatment of growing skull fractures | date=April 1995 | author=Muhonen MG, Piper JG, Menezes AH | journal=Surg Neurol | pages=367\u201372; discussion 372\u20133 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 12632116 | doi=10.1007/s00701-002-1054-y | volume=145 | title=Growing skull fracture of the posterior cranial fossa and of the orbital roof | date=March 2003 | author=Caffo M, German\u00f2 A, Caruso G, Meli F, Calisto A, Tomasello F | journal=Acta Neurochir (Wien) | pages=201\u20138; discussion 208 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 9781277 | volume=140 | title=The natural history of late diagnosed or untreated growing skull fractures: report on two cases | year=1998 | author=Ziyal IM, Aydin Y, T\u00fcrkmen CS, Salas E, Kaya AR, Ozveren F | journal=Acta Neurochir (Wien) | pages=651\u20134 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 2770958 | doi=10.1055/s-2008-1054014 | volume=32 | title=Growing fractures: an unusual complication of head injuries in pediatric patients | date=July 1989 | author=Locatelli D, Messina AL, Bonfanti N, Pezzotta S, Gajno TM | journal=Neurochirurgia (Stuttg) | pages=101\u20134 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 4093801 | volume=29 | title=Growing skull fractures of childhood. Case report and review of 132 cases | year=1985 | author=Pezzotta S, Silvani V, Gaetani P, Spanu G, Rondini G | journal=J Neurosurg Sci | pages=129\u201335 }}</ref>\n\n====Cranial burst fracture====\nA cranial burst skull fracture usually occurring with severe injuries in infants less than 1 year of age is a closed, diastatic skull fracture with cerebral extrusion beyond the outer table of the skull under the intact [[scalp]].\n\nAcute scalp swelling is associated with this type of fracture. In equivocal cases without immediate scalp swelling the diagnosis may be made via the use of [[magnetic resonance imaging]] thus insuring more prompt treatment and avoiding the development of a \"growing skull fracture\".<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 8750951 | volume=11 | title=Cranial burst fracture in infants: acute recognition and management | date=December 1995 | author=Donahue DJ, Sanford RA, Muhlbauer MS, Chadduck WM | journal=Childs Nerv Syst | pages=692\u20137 }}</ref>\n\n===Compound fracture===\n[[File:Meninges-en.svg|thumb|Compound skull fractures occur when all layers protecting the brain have been breached from the [[epidermis (skin)|epidermis]] to the [[meninges]] allowing outside environmental contact with the skull cavity]] \nA fracture in conjunction with an overlying [[laceration]] that tears the epidermis and the [[meninges]]\u2014or runs through the [[paranasal sinuses]] and the [[middle ear]] structures, putting the outside environment in contact with the cranial cavity\u2014is a compound fracture.\n\nCompound fractures may either be clean or contaminated. Intracranial air ([[pneumocephalus]]) may occur in compound skull fractures.<ref>Fundamentals of diagnostic radiology by  William E. Brant, Clyde A. Helms p.56</ref>\n\nThe most serious complication of compound skull fractures is infection. Increased risk factors for infection include visible contamination, meningeal tear, loose bone fragments and presenting for treatment more than eight hours after initial injury.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Rehman L, Ghani E, Hussain A | display-authors = etal | date = Mar 2007 | title = Infection in compound depressed fracture of the skull | url = | journal = J Coll Physicians Surg Pak | volume = 17 | issue = 3| pages = 140\u20133 | pmid = 17374298 }}</ref>\n\n====Compound elevated fracture====\nA compound elevated skull fracture is a rare type of skull fracture where the fractured bone is elevated above the intact outer table of the skull. This type of skull fracture is always compound in nature. It can be caused during an assault with a weapon where the initial blow penetrates the skull and the underlying meninges and, on withdrawal, the weapon lifts the fractured portion of the skull outward. It can also be caused the skull rotating while being struck in a case of blunt force trauma, the skull rotating while striking an inanimate object as in a fall, or it may occur during transfer of a patient after an initial compound head injury.<ref>Elevated skull fracture[www.ijntonline.com/Dec07/abstracts/abs12.PDF]</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 16630918 | doi=10.1016/j.surneu.2005.07.010 | volume=65 | title=Compound elevated skull fracture: a forgotten type of skull fracture | date=May 2006 | author=Adeolu AA, Shokunbi MT, Malomo AO, Komolafe EO, Olateju SO, Amusa YB | journal=Surg Neurol | pages=503\u20135 }}</ref>\n\n==Anatomy==\n{{multiple image\n | align     = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | image1    = Cranial bones en.svg\n | width1    = 208\n | caption1  = [[Lateral (anatomy)|Lateral view]] of the human skull with the [[neurocranium]] highlighted.\n | image2    = Three bone layers of the cranial vault.jpg\n | width2    = 290\n | caption2  = The three bone layers of the skull.\n}}\nThe human skull is anatomically divided into two parts: the [[neurocranium]], formed by eight cranial bones that houses and protect the brain\u2014and the facial skeleton ([[facial skeleton|viscerocranium]]) composed of fourteen bones, not including the three [[ossicle]]s of the inner ear.<ref>Anne M. Gilroy: : Atlas of Anatomy. P.454; Thime Medical Publishers Inc. (2008) {{ISBN|1-60406-151-0}}</ref>  The term ''skull fracture'' typically means fractures to the neurocranium, while fractures of the facial portion of the skull are ''[[facial fracture]]s'', or if the jaw is fractured, a ''[[mandibular fracture]]''.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 6950035 | volume=40 | title=Fractures of the mandible: a review of 580 cases | date=January 1982 | author=Olson RA, Fonseca RJ, Zeitler DL, Osbon DB | journal=J. Oral Maxillofac. Surg. | pages=23\u20138 }}</ref>\n\nThe eight cranial bones  are separated by [[Suture (joint)|suture]]s : one [[frontal bone]], two [[parietal bone]]s, two [[temporal bone]]s, one [[occipital bone]], one [[sphenoid bone]], and one [[ethmoid bone]].<ref>Leon Schlossberg, George D. Zuidema, Johns: The Johns Hopkins Atlas of Human Functional Anatomy, p.5; The Johns Hopkins University Press; (1997) {{ISBN|0-8018-5652-3}}</ref>\n\nThe bones of the skull are in three layers: the hard compact layer of the external table (''[[External lamina|lamina externa]]''), the [[diplo\u00eb]] (a spongy layer of [[red bone marrow]] in the middle, and the compact layer of the inner table (''Lamina interna'').<ref>Johannes Lang: Skull base and related structures: atlas of clinical anatomy. P.208. F.K.Schattauer, Germany;(July 1999) {{ISBN|3-7945-1947-7}}</ref>\n\nSkull thickness is variable, depending on location. Thus the traumatic impact required to cause a fracture depends on the impact site. The skull is thick at the [[glabella]], the [[external occipital protuberance]], the [[mastoid process]]es, and the external angular process. Areas of the skull that are covered with muscle have no underlying diplo\u00eb formation between the internal and external lamina, which results in thin bone more susceptible to fractures.\n\nSkull fractures occur more easily at the thin squamous [[Squama temporalis|temporal]] and [[parietal bone]]s, the [[sphenoid sinus]], the [[foramen magnum]] (the opening at the base of the skull that the spinal cord passes through), the [[Petrous part of the temporal bone|petrous temporal ridge]], and the inner portions of the [[Greater wing of sphenoid bone|sphenoid wings]] at the base of the skull. The [[middle cranial fossa]], a depression at the base of the cranial cavity forms the thinnest part of the skull and is thus the weakest part. This area of the cranial floor is weakened further by the presence of multiple [[Foramina of the skull|foramina]] as a result this section is at higher risk for basilar skull fractures to occur. Other areas more susceptible to fractures are the [[cribriform plate]], the roof of orbits in the [[anterior cranial fossa]], and the areas between the mastoid and [[dural sinus]]es in the [[posterior cranial fossa]].<ref>[[Medscape]]: Ali Nawaz Khan: Imaging in Skull Fractures [http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/343764-overview]</ref>\n\n==Prognosis==\nChildren with a simple skull fracture without other concerns are at low risk of a bad outcome and rarely require aggressive treatment.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bressan|first1=S|last2=Marchetto|first2=L|last3=Lyons|first3=TW|last4=Monuteaux|first4=MC|last5=Freedman|first5=SB|last6=Da Dalt|first6=L|last7=Nigrovic|first7=LE|title=A Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis of the Management and Outcomes of Isolated Skull Fractures in Children|journal=Annals of Emergency Medicine|volume=71|issue=6|pages=714\u2013724.e2|date=23 November 2017|doi=10.1016/j.annemergmed.2017.10.014|pmid=29174834}}</ref>\n\nThe presence of a concussion or skull fracture in people after trauma without intracranial [[hemorrhage]] or [[Focal neurologic signs|focal neurologic deficits]] was indicated in long term cognitive impairments and emotional lability at nearly double the rate as those patients without either complication.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 17215737 | doi=10.1097/TA.0b013e31802ce9bd | volume=62 | title=Long-term cognitive, emotional, and functional outcomes in trauma intensive care unit survivors without intracranial hemorrhage | date=January 2007 | author=Jackson JC, Obremskey W, Bauer R | display-authors = etal | journal=J Trauma | pages=80\u20138}}</ref>\n\nThose with a skull fracture were shown to have \"neuropsychological dysfunction, even in the absence of intracranial pathology or more severe disturbance of consciousness on the GCS\".<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 9058000 | volume=11 | title=Impact of skull fracture on neuropsychological functioning following closed head injury | date=March 1997 | author=Smith-Seemiller L, Lovell MR, Smith S, Markosian N, Townsend RN | journal=Brain Inj | pages=191\u20136 | doi=10.1080/026990597123638}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Le Fort fracture of skull|Le Fort facial fracture]]\n*[[Facial trauma|Facial fracture]]\n*[[Mandibular fracture]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Forensic Neuropathology By Jan E. Leestma Publisher: CRC Press; 2 edition (October 14, 2008) Language: English {{ISBN|0-8493-9167-9}} {{ISBN|978-0849391675}}\n*Neuroimaging: Clinical and Physical Principles By Robert A. Zimmerman, Wendell A. Gibby, Raymond F. Carmody Publisher: Springer; 1st edition (January 15, 2000) Language: English {{ISBN|0387949631}} {{ISBN|978-0-387-94963-5}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|  ICD10 = S02 \n|  ICD9 = {{ICD9|800.0}}-{{ICD9|804.9}} \n| DiseasesDB=12169\n|  MedlinePlus = 000060 \n|  MeshID = D012887 \n}}\n*[http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/343764-overview Medscape: Imaging in Skull Fractures]\n*[https://archive.is/20121210134516/http://rad.usuhs.edu/medpix/medpix.html?mode=factoid_images&recnum=1543 Growing skull fracture at Medpix]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051106231525/http://www.radiology.co.uk/srs-x/tutors/cttrauma/tutor.htm \"Tutorial: CT in Head Trauma\"]\n*[http://www.emedicine.com/med/topic2820.htm Head Trauma at Emedicine.com]\n* [http://rad.usuhs.edu/medpix/parent.php3?mode=image_finder&action=search&srchstr=skull%20fracture&srch_type=all#top Skull Fractures at MedPix]\n\n{{Fractures}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skull Fracture}}\n[[Category:Bone fractures]]\n[[Category:Neurotrauma]]\n[[Category:Injuries of head]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new) \n| name            = Skull fracture \n| image           = Depressed skull fracture.jpg \n| caption         = A piece of a [[skull]] with a depressed skull fracture \n| pronounce       =  \n| field           =  \n| synonyms        =  \n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n\nA '''skull fracture''' is a break in one or more of the eight bones that form the cranial portion of the [[human skull|skull]], usually occurring as a result of [[blunt force trauma]].  If the force of the impact is excessive, the [[bone]] may fracture at or near the site of the impact and cause damage to the underlying structures within the skull such as the [[Meninges|membranes]], [[blood vessel]]s, and [[Human brain|brain]]. \n\nWhile an uncomplicated skull fracture can occur without associated  physical or [[neurological]] damage and is in itself usually not clinically significant, a fracture in healthy bone indicates that a substantial amount of force has been applied and increases the possibility of associated [[traumatic brain injury|injury]]. Any significant blow to the head results in a [[concussion]], with or without loss of [[consciousness]].\n\nA fracture in conjunction with an overlying [[laceration]] that tears the [[epidermis (skin)|epidermis]] and the [[meninges]], or runs through the [[paranasal sinuses]] and the [[middle ear]] structures, bringing the outside environment into contact with the cranial cavity is called a compound fracture. Compound fractures can either be clean or contaminated.\n\nThere are four major types of skull fractures: linear, depressed, diastatic, and basilar. Linear fractures are the most common, and usually require no intervention for the fracture itself. Depressed fractures are usually [[Bone fracture|comminuted]], with broken portions of bone displaced inward\u2014and may require surgical intervention to repair underlying tissue damage. Diastatic fractures widen the sutures of the skull and usually affect children under three. Basilar fractures are in the bones at the base of the skull.\n{{TOC limit}}\n\n==Types==\n\n===Linear fracture===\nLinear skull fractures are breaks in the bone that transverse the full thickness of the skull from the outer to inner table. They are usually fairly straight with no bone displacement. The common cause of injury is blunt force trauma where the impact energy transferred over a wide area of the skull.\n\nLinear skull fractures are usually of little clinical significance unless they parallel in close proximity or transverse a [[Suture (joint)|suture]], or they involve a venous sinus groove or vascular channel. The resulting complications may include suture [[diastasis (pathology)|diastasis]], [[venous sinus thrombosis]], and [[epidural hematoma]]. In young children, although rare, the possibility exists of developing a growing skull fracture especially if the fracture occurs in the [[parietal bone]].<ref>Haar FL. Complication of linear skull fracture in young children. Am J Dis Child. 1975 Oct;129(10):1197-200. {{PMID|1190143}}</ref>\n\n===Depressed fracture===\n[[File:Depressed skull fracture2.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Depressed skull fracture.]]\nA depressed skull fracture is a type of fracture usually resulting from blunt force trauma, such as getting struck with a hammer, rock or getting kicked in the head. These types of fractures\u2014which occur in 11% of severe head injuries\u2014are comminuted fractures in which broken bones displace inward. Depressed skull fractures present a high risk of increased [[intracranial pressure|pressure on the brain]], or a hemorrhage to the brain that crushes the delicate tissue.\n\nCompound depressed skull fractures occur when there is a laceration over the fracture, putting the internal cranial cavity in contact with the outside environment, increasing the risk of contamination and infection. In complex depressed fractures, the [[dura mater]] is torn. Depressed skull fractures may require [[neurosurgery|surgery]] to lift the bones off the brain if they are pressing on it by making burr holes on the adjacent normal skull.<ref name=\"singh\">Singh J and Stock A. 2006. [http://www.emedicine.com/ped/topic929.htm \"Head Trauma.\"] Emedicine.com. Retrieved on January 26, 2007.</ref>\n\n===Diastatic fracture===\n[[File:Cleidocranial2.jpg|thumb|right|180px|cranial abnormalities in cleidocranial dysplasia including diastatic sutures.]]\nDiastatic fractures occur when the fracture line transverses\none or more sutures of the skull causing a widening of the suture. While this type of fracture is usually seen in infants and young children as the sutures are not yet fused it can also occur in adults. When a diastatic fracture occurs in adults it usually affects the [[lambdoidal suture]] as this suture does not fully fuse in adults until about the age of 60. Other than that Most adult diastatic fractures are caused by severe head injuries. Due to the trauma, diastatic fracture occurs with the collapse of the surrounding head bones. It makes the delicate tissue to be crushed, like depressed skull fracture.\n\n\nDiastatic fractures can occur with different types of fractures and it is also possible for diastasis of the cranial sutures to occur without a concomitant  fracture. Sutural diastasis may also occur in various congenital disorders such as [[cleidocranial dysplasia]] and [[osteogenesis imperfecta]].<ref>Paterson CR, Burns J, McAllion SJ. Am J Med Genet. 1993 Jan 15;45(2):187-92.Osteogenesis imperfecta: the distinction from child abuse and the recognition of a variant form.\n{{PMID|8456801}}</ref><ref>Kanda M, Kabe S, Kanki T, Sato J, Hasegawa Y. Cleidocranial dysplasia: a case report No Shinkei Geka. 1997 Dec;25(12):1109-13. {{PMID|9430147}}</ref><ref>Sabini RC, Elkowitz DE. J Am Osteopath Assoc. 2006 Oct;106(10):600-4. Significance of differences in patency among cranial sutures.{{PMID|17122029}}</ref><ref>Pirouzmand F, Muhajarine N. Craniofac Surg. 2008 Jan;19(1):27-36. Definition of topographic organization of skull profile in normal population and its implications on the role of the sutures in skull morphology.{{PMID|18216661}}</ref>\n\n===Basilar fracture===\n{{main|Basilar skull fracture}}\n[[File:Sch\u00e4delbasis1.jpg|thumb|130px|Superior view of the skull base.]]\n[[Basilar skull fracture]]s are linear fractures that occur in the floor of the cranial vault (skull base), which require more force to cause than other areas of the neurocranium. Thus they are rare, occurring as the only fracture in only 4% of severe head injury patients.\n\nBasilar fractures have characteristic signs: blood in the [[Paranasal sinus|sinuses]]; a clear fluid called [[cerebrospinal fluid]] (CSF) leaking from the nose ([[rhinorrhea]]) or ears ([[otorrhea]]); [[periorbital]] [[ecchymosis]]  often called '[[raccoon eyes]]'<ref>Herbella FA, Mudo M, Delmonti C. ''et al.'' Injury. 2001 Dec;32(10):745-7. 'Raccoon eyes' (periorbital haematoma) as a sign of skull base fracture. {{PMID|11754879}}</ref> (bruising of the orbits of the eyes that result from blood collecting there as it leaks from the fracture site); and retro[[Ear|auricular]] ecchymosis known as \"[[Battle's sign]]\" (bruising over the mastoid process).<ref>{{cite journal | author = Tubbs RS, Shoja MM, Loukas M | display-authors = etal | date = Jan 2010 | title = William Henry Battle and Battle's sign: mastoid ecchymosis as an indicator of basilar skull fracture | url = | journal = J Neurosurg | volume = 112 | issue = 1| pages = 186\u20138 | pmid = 19392601 | doi = 10.3171/2008.8.JNS08241 }}</ref>\n\n===Growing fracture===\nA growing skull fracture (GSF) also known as a craniocerebral erosion or leptomeningeal cyst<ref>Irabor PF, Akhigbe AO. West Afr J Med. 2010 Jan-Feb;29(1):44-6. Leptomeningeal cyst in a child after head trauma: a case report.{{PMID|20496339}}</ref> due to the usual development of a cystic mass filled with cerebrospinal fluid  is a rare complication of head injury usually associated with linear skull fractures of the parietal bone in children under 3. It has been reported in older children in atypical regions of the skull such as the basiooccipital and the base of the skull base and in association with other types of skull fractures. It is characterized by a diastatic enlargement of the fracture.\n\nVarious factors are associated with the development of a GSF. The primary causitive factor is a tear in the [[dura mater]]. The skull fracture enlarges due, in part, to the rapid physiologic growth of the brain that occurs in young children, and brain [[cerebrospinal fluid]] (CSF) pulsations in the underlying [[Leptomeninges|leptomenigeal]] [[cyst]]ic mass.<ref>Gupta SK, Reddy NM, Khosla VK, Mathuriya SN, Shama BS, Pathak A, Tewari MK, Kak VK. Growing skull fractures: a clinical study of 41 patients. Acta Neurochir (Wien). 1997;139(10):928-32.\n{{PMID|9401652}}</ref><ref>Ersahin Y, G\u00fclmen V, Palali I, Mutluer S. Growing skull fractures (craniocerebral erosion). Neurosurg Rev. 2000 Sep;23(3):139-44. {{PMID|11086738}}</ref><ref>Muhonen MG, Piper JG, Menezes AH. Surg Neurol. 1995 Apr;43(4):367-72; discussion 372-3. Pathogenesis and treatment of growing skull fractures.{{PMID|7792708}}</ref><ref>Caffo M, German\u00f2 A, Caruso G, Meli F, Calisto A, Tomasello F. Acta Neurochir (Wien). 2003 Mar;145(3):201-8; discussion 208. Growing skull fracture of the posterior cranial fossa and of the orbital roof. {{PMID|12632116}}</ref><ref>Ziyal IM, Aydin Y, T\u00fcrkmen CS, Salas E, Kaya AR, Ozveren F. Acta Neurochir (Wien). 1998;140(7):651-4. The natural history of late diagnosed or untreated growing skull fractures: report on two cases.{{PMID|9781277}}</ref><ref>Locatelli D, Messina AL, Bonfanti N, Pezzotta S, Gajno TM. Growing fractures: an unusual complication of head injuries in pediatric patients. Neurochirurgia (Stuttg). 1989 Jul;32(4):101-4. {{PMID|2770958}}</ref><ref>Pezzotta S, Silvani V, Gaetani P, Spanu G, Rondini G. J Neurosurg Sci. 1985 Apr-Jun;29(2):129-35. Growing skull fractures of childhood. Case report and review of 132 cases. {{PMID|4093801}}</ref>\n\n====Cranial burst fracture====\nA cranial burst skull fracture usually occurring with severe injuries in infants less than 1 year of age is a closed, diastatic skull fracture with cerebral extrusion beyond the outer table of the skull under the intact [[scalp]].\n\nAcute scalp swelling is associated with this type of fracture. In equivocal cases without immediate scalp swelling the diagnosis may be made via the use of [[magnetic resonance imaging]] thus insuring more prompt treatment and avoiding the development of a \"growing skull fracture\".<ref>Donahue DJ, Sanford RA, Muhlbauer MS, ''et al.'' Cranial burst fracture in infants: acute recognition and management. Childs Nerv Syst. 1995 Dec;11(12):692-7. {{PMID|8750951}}</ref>\n\n===Compound fracture===\n[[File:Meninges-en.svg|thumb|Compound skull fractures occur when all layers protecting the brain have been breached from the [[epidermis (skin)|epidermis]] to the [[meninges]] allowing outside environmental contact with the skull cavity]] \nA fracture in conjunction with an overlying [[laceration]] that tears the epidermis and the [[meninges]]\u2014or runs through the [[paranasal sinuses]] and the [[middle ear]] structures, putting the outside environment in contact with the cranial cavity\u2014is a compound fracture.\n\nCompound fractures may either be clean or contaminated. Intracranial air ([[pneumocephalus]]) may occur in compound skull fractures.<ref>Fundamentals of diagnostic radiology by  William E. Brant, Clyde A. Helms p.56</ref>\n\nThe most serious complication of compound skull fractures is infection. Increased risk factors for infection include visible contamination, meningeal tear, loose bone fragments and presenting for treatment more than eight hours after initial injury.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Rehman L, Ghani E, Hussain A | display-authors = etal | date = Mar 2007 | title = Infection in compound depressed fracture of the skull | url = | journal = J Coll Physicians Surg Pak | volume = 17 | issue = 3| pages = 140\u20133 | pmid = 17374298 }}</ref>\n\n====Compound elevated fracture====\nA compound elevated skull fracture is a rare type of skull fracture where the fractured bone is elevated above the intact outer table of the skull. This type of skull fracture is always compound in nature. It can be caused during an assault with a weapon where the initial blow penetrates the skull and the underlying meninges and, on withdrawal, the weapon lifts the fractured portion of the skull outward. It can also be caused the skull rotating while being struck in a case of blunt force trauma, the skull rotating while striking an inanimate object as in a fall, or it may occur during transfer of a patient after an initial compound head injury.<ref>Elevated skull fracture[www.ijntonline.com/Dec07/abstracts/abs12.PDF]</ref><ref>Adeolu AA, Shokunbi MT, Malomo AO, ''et al.'' Compound elevated skull fracture: a forgotten type of skull fracture. Surg Neurol. 2006 May;65(5):5\n{{PMID|16630918}}</ref>\n==Anatomy==\n{{multiple image\n | align     = right\n | direction = horizontal\n | image1    = Cranial bones en.svg\n | width1    = 208\n | caption1  = [[Lateral (anatomy)|Lateral view]] of the human skull with the [[neurocranium]] highlighted.\n | image2    = Three bone layers of the cranial vault.jpg\n | width2    = 290\n | caption2  = The three bone layers of the skull.\n}}\nThe human skull is anatomically divided into two parts: the [[neurocranium]], formed by eight cranial bones that houses and protect the brain\u2014and the facial skeleton ([[facial skeleton|viscerocranium]]) composed of fourteen bones, not including the three [[ossicle]]s of the inner ear.<ref>Anne M. Gilroy: : Atlas of Anatomy. P.454; Thime Medical Publishers Inc. (2008) {{ISBN|1-60406-151-0}}</ref>  The term ''skull fracture'' typically means fractures to the neurocranium, while fractures of the facial portion of the skull are ''[[facial fracture]]s'', or if the jaw is fractured, a ''[[mandibular fracture]]''.<ref>Olson RA, Fonseca RJ, Zeitler DL, ''et al.'' Fractures of the mandible: a review of 580 cases. J Oral Maxillofac Surg. 1982 Jan;40(1):23-8. {{PMID|6950035}}</ref>\n\nThe eight cranial bones  are separated by [[Suture (joint)|suture]]s : one [[frontal bone]], two [[parietal bone]]s, two [[temporal bone]]s, one [[occipital bone]], one [[sphenoid bone]], and one [[ethmoid bone]].<ref>Leon Schlossberg, George D. Zuidema, Johns: The Johns Hopkins Atlas of Human Functional Anatomy, p.5; The Johns Hopkins University Press; (1997) {{ISBN|0-8018-5652-3}}</ref>\n\nThe bones of the skull are in three layers: the hard compact layer of the external table (''[[External lamina|lamina externa]]''), the [[diplo\u00eb]] (a spongy layer of [[red bone marrow]] in the middle, and the compact layer of the inner table (''Lamina interna'').<ref>Johannes Lang: Skull base and related structures: atlas of clinical anatomy. P.208. F.K.Schattauer, Germany;(July 1999) {{ISBN|3-7945-1947-7}}</ref>\n\nSkull thickness is variable, depending on location. Thus the traumatic impact required to cause a fracture depends on the impact site. The skull is thick at the [[glabella]], the [[external occipital protuberance]], the [[mastoid process]]es, and the external angular process. Areas of the skull that are covered with muscle have no underlying diplo\u00eb formation between the internal and external lamina, which results in thin bone more susceptible to fractures.\n\nSkull fractures occur more easily at the thin squamous [[Squama temporalis|temporal]] and [[parietal bone]]s, the [[sphenoid sinus]], the [[foramen magnum]] (the opening at the base of the skull that the spinal cord passes through), the [[Petrous part of the temporal bone|petrous temporal ridge]], and the inner portions of the [[Greater wing of sphenoid bone|sphenoid wings]] at the base of the skull. The [[middle cranial fossa]], a depression at the base of the cranial cavity forms the thinnest part of the skull and is thus the weakest part. This area of the cranial floor is weakened further by the presence of multiple [[Foramina of the skull|foramina]] as a result this section is at higher risk for basilar skull fractures to occur. Other areas more susceptible to fractures are the [[cribriform plate]], the roof of orbits in the [[anterior cranial fossa]], and the areas between the mastoid and [[dural sinus]]es in the [[posterior cranial fossa]].<ref>[[Medscape]]: Ali Nawaz Khan: Imaging in Skull Fractures [http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/343764-overview]</ref>\n\n==Prognosis==\nChildren with a simple skull fracture without other concerns are at low risk of a bad outcome and rarely require aggressive treatment.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Bressan|first1=S|last2=Marchetto|first2=L|last3=Lyons|first3=TW|last4=Monuteaux|first4=MC|last5=Freedman|first5=SB|last6=Da Dalt|first6=L|last7=Nigrovic|first7=LE|title=A Systematic Review and Meta-Analysis of the Management and Outcomes of Isolated Skull Fractures in Children|journal=Annals of Emergency Medicine|volume=71|issue=6|pages=714\u2013724.e2|date=23 November 2017|doi=10.1016/j.annemergmed.2017.10.014|pmid=29174834}}</ref>\n\nThe presence of a concussion or skull fracture in people after trauma without intracranial [[hemorrhage]] or [[Focal neurologic signs|focal neurologic deficits]] was indicated in long term cognitive impairments and emotional lability at nearly double the rate as those patients without either complication.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 17215737 | doi=10.1097/TA.0b013e31802ce9bd | volume=62 | title=Long-term cognitive, emotional, and functional outcomes in trauma intensive care unit survivors without intracranial hemorrhage | date=January 2007 | author=Jackson JC, Obremskey W, Bauer R | display-authors = etal | journal=J Trauma | pages=80\u20138}}</ref>\n\nThose with a skull fracture were shown to have \"neuropsychological dysfunction, even in the absence of intracranial pathology or more severe disturbance of consciousness on the GCS\".<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 9058000 | volume=11 | title=Impact of skull fracture on neuropsychological functioning following closed head injury | date=March 1997 | author=Smith-Seemiller L, Lovell MR, Smith S, Markosian N, Townsend RN | journal=Brain Inj | pages=191\u20136 | doi=10.1080/026990597123638}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Le Fort fracture of skull|Le Fort facial fracture]]\n*[[Facial trauma|Facial fracture]]\n*[[Mandibular fracture]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*Forensic Neuropathology By Jan E. Leestma Publisher: CRC Press; 2 edition (October 14, 2008) Language: English {{ISBN|0-8493-9167-9}} {{ISBN|978-0849391675}}\n*Neuroimaging: Clinical and Physical Principles By Robert A. Zimmerman, Wendell A. Gibby, Raymond F. Carmody Publisher: Springer; 1st edition (January 15, 2000) Language: English {{ISBN|0387949631}} {{ISBN|978-0-387-94963-5}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|  ICD10 = S02 \n|  ICD9 = {{ICD9|800.0}}-{{ICD9|804.9}} \n| DiseasesDB=12169\n|  MedlinePlus = 000060 \n|  MeshID = D012887 \n}}\n*[http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/343764-overview Medscape: Imaging in Skull Fractures]\n*[https://archive.is/20121210134516/http://rad.usuhs.edu/medpix/medpix.html?mode=factoid_images&recnum=1543 Growing skull fracture at Medpix]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051106231525/http://www.radiology.co.uk/srs-x/tutors/cttrauma/tutor.htm \"Tutorial: CT in Head Trauma\"]\n*[http://www.emedicine.com/med/topic2820.htm Head Trauma at Emedicine.com]\n* [http://rad.usuhs.edu/medpix/parent.php3?mode=image_finder&action=search&srchstr=skull%20fracture&srch_type=all#top Skull Fractures at MedPix]\n\n\n{{Fractures}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skull Fracture}}\n[[Category:Bone fractures]]\n[[Category:Neurotrauma]]\n[[Category:Injuries of head]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "Journal cites:, templated journal cites", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skull_fracture"}
{"title_page": "Pradeep John", "text_new": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|weather blogger}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-suffix   = Independent Weatherman\n| name = Pradeep John\n| image =\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1982}}\n| birth_place = Melpuram, Pacode,<br>[[Kanyakumari District]]\n| nationality = [[India|Indian]]\n| education = {{Plainlist| \n* [[Sathyabama University]] ([[B.E]])  \n* [[Madras University]] ([[Master of Business Administration|M.B.A]]) \n }} \n| other_names = \n| years_active = \n| known_for = \n| signature = \n| office = \n}}\n\n'''Pradeep John''', popularly known as '''Tamil Nadu Weatherman''',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dtnext.in/News/TamilNadu/2018/10/01044140/1090518/Fishermen-panic-as-Windy-predicts-cyclone.vpf|title= Fishermen panic as \u2018Windy\u2019 predicts cyclone| work=dtnext.in|accessdate=1 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2019/jun/20/will-rains-continue-in-chennai-tamil-nadu-weatherman-comes-out-with-the-answer-1992868.html|title= Will rains continue in Chennai? Tamil Nadu Weatherman comes out with the answer| work=newindianexpress.com|accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref> is an Indian self-taught weather expert &  blogger from [[Tamil Nadu]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-weatherman-pradeep-john-receives-inspirational-role-model-award-cii-connect-2019-112452|title= TN weatherman Pradeep John receives Inspirational Role Model Award at CII Connect 2019| work=thenewsminute.com|accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/chennai-rain-after-196-days-parts-of-city-receives-showers/articleshow/69873617.cms|title= Chennai rain: After 196 days, parts of city receive showers| work=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/858252/meet-pradeep-john-an-obscure-blogger-who-became-tamil-nadus-trusted-weatherman|title=An self-taught weather expert.|last=|first=|date=Nov 19, 2017|website=scroll.in|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It's not an exaggeration when we say that his forecasts are more closely followed by the people of [[Chennai]] than the forecasts shared by the [[India Meteorological Department]] during the season of monsoon. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parentcircle.com/article/tamil-nadu-weatherman-pradeep-john-chennai-weather-may-be-hotter-than-usual-this-summer/|title= Chennai Weather: Expert Views From Tamil Nadu Weatherman| work=parentcircle.com}}</ref> His [[blogging]] journey started in 2008 when he began to write about [[weather]] & [[rainfall]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://scroll.in/article/858252/meet-pradeep-john-an-obscure-blogger-who-became-tamil-nadus-trusted-weatherman|title= Meet Pradeep John, an obscure blogger who became Tamil Nadu\u2019s trusted weatherman| work=scroll.in}}</ref> Later in 2014, he made his first [[social media]] presence too. His fame in social media skyrocketed after his accurate predictions during the 2015 [[2015 South India floods|Chennai floods]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thebetterindia.com/111285/tamil-nadu-weatherman-weather-forecasts-facebook/|title= How a Common Man Became TN\u2019s Weatherman, Whose Weather Forecasts Are Trusted by 2 Lakh People| work=thebetterindia.com}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nPradeep John was born in the [[Kanyakumari district]] and lives in Chennai now. He grew an interest in weather at a very early age of 12 since he was very much fascinated by the power of nature.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lbb.in/chennai/tamil-nadu-weather-man-chennai/|title= Take A Rain Check? The Tamil Nadu Weather Man Is Here To Predict Chennai's Forecasts| work=lbb.in}}</ref>  He did his schooling at [[SBOA Matriculation and Higher Secondary School, Chennai | SBOA Matriculation School]] and graduated B.E in Computer science and Engineering from [[Sathyabama University]]. He also holds an MBA in Finance from [[Madras University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theweekendleader.com/Heroism/2630/the-rain-man.html|title= Rain, rain, don\u2019t go away, weatherman Johnny wants to play| work=theweekendleader.com|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref> Pradeep John married Hannah Shalini who is a housewife and the couple has a daughter Laura Abigail.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ritzmagazine.in/tracking-the-weather-by-storm-pradeep-johnby-sanjay-pinto/|title= Tracking the weather by storm! \u2013 Pradeep John By Sanjay Pinto| work=ritzmagazine.in|accessdate=31 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn 2008 Pradeep John joined India Infoline as a relationship manager.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theweekendleader.com/Heroism/2630/the-rain-man.html|title= Rain, rain, don\u2019t go away, weatherman Johnny wants to play| work=theweekendleader.com|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref>  Currently,{{when?|date=April 2020}} he works as a Deputy Manager at Tamil Nadu Urban Infrastructure Financial Services Limited (TNUIFSL).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.livechennai.com/detailnews.asp?newsid=37568|title= A common man to a revered weatherman. Everything you need to know| work=livechennai.com|accessdate=1 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and Honors==\n* In 2018 Pride of Tamil Nadu Award - Inspirational Achiever.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2018/mar/26/and-the-pride-of-tamil-nadu-award-goes-to-1792825.html|title= And the Pride of Tamil Nadu Award goes to| work=newindianexpress.com|accessdate=26 March 2018}}</ref>\n* In 2019 CII Connect Award - Inspirational Role Model Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-weatherman-pradeep-john-receives-inspirational-role-model-award-cii-connect-2019-112452|title= TN weatherman Pradeep John receives Inspirational Role Model Award at CII Connect 2019| work=thenewsminute.com|accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref> \n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.facebook.com/tamilnaduweatherman/ Official Facebook]\n* [https://twitter.com/praddy06 Official Twitter]\n\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian Tamil academics]]\n[[Category:People from Kanyakumari district]]\n[[Category:Engineers from Tamil Nadu]]\n", "text_old": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|weather blogger}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-suffix   = Independent Weatherman\n| name = Pradeep John\n| image =\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1982}}\n| birth_place = Melpuram, Pacode,<br>[[Kanyakumari District]]\n| nationality = [[India|Indian]]\n| education = {{Plainlist| \n* [[Sathyabama University]] ([[B.E]])  \n* [[Madras University]] ([[Master of Business Administration|M.B.A]]) \n }} \n| other_names = \n| years_active = \n| known_for = \n| signature = \n| office = \n}}\n\n'''Pradeep John''', popularly known as '''Tamil Nadu Weatherman''',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dtnext.in/News/TamilNadu/2018/10/01044140/1090518/Fishermen-panic-as-Windy-predicts-cyclone.vpf|title= Fishermen panic as \u2018Windy\u2019 predicts cyclone| work=dtnext.in|accessdate=1 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/cities/chennai/2019/jun/20/will-rains-continue-in-chennai-tamil-nadu-weatherman-comes-out-with-the-answer-1992868.html|title= Will rains continue in Chennai? Tamil Nadu Weatherman comes out with the answer| work=newindianexpress.com|accessdate=20 June 2019}}</ref> is an Indian self-taught weather expert &  blogger from [[Tamil Nadu]]. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-weatherman-pradeep-john-receives-inspirational-role-model-award-cii-connect-2019-112452|title= TN weatherman Pradeep John receives Inspirational Role Model Award at CII Connect 2019| work=thenewsminute.com|accessdate=17 November 2019}}</ref> <ref>{{cite w